'''Catholic Slavs''' and '''Slavic Catholic''' are terms used for the historically and/or predominantly Catholic Slavic ethnic groups and nations and for the [[history of Catholicism]] among the [[Slavic peoples]]; especially amongst the [[West Slavs]]. The Catholic Slavic nations include all [[West Slavs]] ([[Poles]], [[Czechs]] and [[Slovaks]] and all their sub-ethnicities ex. [[Kashubs]], [[Silesians]]) as well as the westernmost [[South Slavs]] ([[Slovenes]] and [[Croats]]).<ref name="Jakelic2016">{{cite book|author=Slavica Jakelic|title=Collectivistic Religions: Religion, Choice, and Identity in Late Modernity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=olY3DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA101|date=23 May 2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-16420-3|pages=101–}}</ref>

==History==
===Middle Ages===
Grand Duke [[Kazimierz IV]] of Lithuania and Poland (r. 1440–92) initiated the Catholicization of [[Kiev Voivodeship|Kiev]] (which was Orthodox) early in his reign.{{sfn|Cooper|2003|p=227}}

===Early modern period===
{{see also|Counter-Reformation}}
The [[Union of Brest]] (1596) saw the official establishment of the [[Uniate]] Church (Eastern it custom and ritual but subscribing to Catholic dogma and submission to the [[Pope]] as head of the Church) in the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]].{{sfn|Cooper|2003|p=227}}

The [[Habsburg Monarchy]] launched a programme of re-Catholicization in [[Bohemia]] and [[Moravia]] in the 1620s.<ref name="Polišenský1971">{{cite book|author=Josef V. Polišenský|title=The Thirty Years War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YvXN_MPfJoEC&pg=PA141|year=1971|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-01868-6|pages=141–}}</ref> The Serbian Orthodox [[Eparchy of Marča]] became Uniate in 1611, although it was part of a conflict between local Catholic and Orthodox clergy over the century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Zlatko Kudelić|title=Marčanska biskupija: Habsburgovci, pravoslavlje i crkvena unija u Hrvatsko-slavonskoj vojnoj krajini (1611. - 1755)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RtFAAQAAIAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Hrvatski Inst. za Povijest|isbn=978-953-6324-62-0}}</ref>

==Modern states==
Modern countries in which historically Catholic Slavs formed a majority or otherwise such [[nation state]]s include:
