== Publication ==

In late 1944 Orwell, worrying about the ephemerality of magazine publication, began to collect a volume of his best essays.{{sfn|Rodden|Rossi|2012|p=70}}  The resulting collection appeared under the imprint of [[Harvill Secker|Secker & Warburg]] on 14 February 1946, with a print-run of 3028 copies.  The following May a second impression of 5632 copies was issued, with some small corrections.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Peter |editor1-last=Davison |editor1-link=Peter Davison (professor) |title=Smothered Under Journalism: 1946 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |series=The Complete Works of George Orwell. Volume 18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0q_yAAAAMAAJ&q=%225,632+copies,+%28already+ordered+before+publication+day%29,+%22&dq=%225,632+copies,+%28already+ordered+before+publication+day%29,+%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=X2FMUsr2PMzu0gXE4IGwBQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA |year=1998 |publisher=Secker & Warburg |location=London |isbn=043620374X |pages=104–105 }}</ref>  The US edition of 5000 copies was published in April 1946 by [[Reynal & Hitchcock]], and retitled ''Dickens, Dali & Others: Studies in Popular Culture''.  A reprint in paperback dropped the subtitle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brown.edu/Facilities/University_Library/libs/hay/collections/orwell/leab.html |title= George Orwell: An Exhibition from the Collection of Daniel J. Leab Brown University, Fall 1997 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2001 |website=John Hay Library: Collections |publisher=Brown University Library |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orwellsociety.com/2012/12/18/peter-davison-on-orwell-dickens-first-and-last/ |title=Dickens – first and last |last1=Davison |first1=Peter |date=18 December 2012 |website=The Orwell Society |accessdate=4 October 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131008005706/http://www.orwellsociety.com/2012/12/18/peter-davison-on-orwell-dickens-first-and-last/ |archivedate=8 October 2013 |df= }}</ref>

== Themes ==

The [[blurb]] to the first edition described some of the essays as being "among the very few attempts that have been made in England to study popular art seriously".  Orwell thought seemingly frivolous popular culture, such as crime fiction, [[Postcard#British seaside postcards|comic postcards]], and the [[Billy Bunter]] stories, to be worth studying for the light it throws on contemporary attitudes.{{sfn|Crick|1994}}  Applying this approach to the subjects considered in ''Critical Essays'' he tended to find that they showed the innovations of his own time to be harsh and unfeeling compared to the old-fashioned humanity of traditional popular forms.{{sfn|Meyers|1997|p=22}}
Another theme is that of literary style, which Orwell thought to be the inevitable result of its writer's world-view and the message he wanted to get across.  He considered the English language of the 1940s to be in a degenerate state, and held that political discourse was inevitably corrupted as a result.{{sfn|Crick|1994}}{{sfn|Rodden|Rossi|2012|p=70}}

== Critical reception ==

Orwell himself, writing before he had completed ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]'', said that he thought ''Critical Essays'' one of his three most important books, along with ''[[Animal Farm]]'' and ''[[Homage to Catalonia]]''.{{sfn|Rodden|Rossi|2012|p=70}}  His contemporaries in the world of criticism also largely saw the book's merits.  The journalist [[T. R. Fyvel|Tosco Fyvel]], writing in ''[[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]]'', acclaimed Orwell as "a national figure as a critic, satirist and political journalist", while disagreeing with Orwell's view that the [[Attlee ministry|Attlee government]] was uncommitted to the introduction a fully socialist society.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rodden |first1=John |title=George Orwell: The Politics of Literary Reputation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-7ihMZgiRgC&pg=PA307 |accessdate=6 October 2012 |year=2009 |origyear=1989 |publisher=Transaction |location=New Brunswick, N.J. |isbn=076580896X |page=307 }}</ref>  In the Catholic paper ''[[The Tablet]]'' [[Evelyn Waugh]] predictably deplored Orwell's lack of religious feeling, but also wrote that the essays "represent at its best the new humanism of the common man", and that Orwell was "outstandingly the wisest" of the new critics.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Giraldi |first1=William |date=11 August 2013 |title=Orwell: Sage of the Century |journal=New Republic |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/114254/george-orwell-life-letters-reviewed-william-giraldi |accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Greene |first1=Donald |author1-link=Donald Greene |chapter=Graham Greene and Evelyn Waugh – "Catholic novelists" |editor1-last=Meyers |editor1-first=Jeffrey |title=Graham Greene: A Revaluation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MbdaAAAAMAAJ&q=%22orwell+is+outstandingly+the+wisest%22&dq=%22orwell+is+outstandingly+the+wisest%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hWJ2UpHwHo2AhQe6kICwBg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA |location=London |publisher=Macmillan |publication-date=1990 |page=23 |isbn=0333458958 |accessdate=3 November 2013 }}</ref>  [[John Middleton Murry|Middleton Murry]], who likewise criticised Orwell's secularism, nevertheless called Orwell and [[Cyril Connolly]] the two most gifted critics of their generation.  [[V. S. Pritchett]] considered the essays "brilliant examples of political anthropology applied to literature by a non-conforming mind".  [[Eric Bentley]] saw the book as "a dirge for nineteenth-century liberalism", and, like [[Irving Howe]], thought it represented Orwell at his best.{{sfn|Meyers|1997|pp=23, 220}}  [[Edmund Wilson]], a critic to whom most others compared Orwell, called him "the only contemporary master" of sociological criticism, praising him for his courage in rejecting the reigning orthodoxies, and for "a prose style that is both downright and disciplined".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Meyers |first1=Jeffrey |title=Edmund Wilson: A Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6bhdAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA272 |location=London |publisher=Constable |publication-date=1995 |pages=272–273 |isbn=0395689937 |accessdate=3 November 2013 }}</ref>  A recent survey of Orwell's work endorses his own high opinion of its importance, calling it "Orwell at his best", a book which "showed Orwell's talent for finding deep meaning in otherwise trivial matters",{{sfn|Rodden|Rossi|2012|p=70}} while [[Bernard Crick]] said that Orwell's essays "may well constitute his lasting claim to greatness as a writer".{{sfn|Crick|1994}}

