==Life cycle==
[[File:Musca domestica mating (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Houseflies mating]]

Each female housefly can lay up to 500 [[egg]]s in a lifetime, in several batches of about 75 to 150. The eggs are white and are about {{convert|1.2|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} in length, and they are deposited by the fly in a suitable place, usually dead and decaying organic matter, such as food waste, carrion, or [[faeces]]. Within a day, larvae ([[maggot]]s) hatch from the eggs; they live and feed where they were laid. They are pale-whitish, {{convert|3|to|9|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} long, thinner at the mouth end, and legless.<ref name=IFAS/> Larval development takes from two weeks, under optimal conditions, to 30 days or more in cooler conditions. The larvae avoid light; the interiors of heaps of animal manure provide nutrient-rich sites and ideal growing conditions, warm, moist, and dark.<ref name=IFAS/>

[[File:The larva and fly of a house fly (Musca domestica). Coloured Wellcome V0022571.jpg|thumb|[[Larva]] and adult, by [[Amedeo John Engel Terzi]] (1872–1956)]]

At the end of their fourth [[instar]], the larvae crawl to a dry, cool place and transform into [[pupa]]e. The pupal case is cylindrical with rounded ends, about {{convert|1.2|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} long, and formed from the last shed larval skin. It is yellowish at first, darkening through red and brown to nearly black as it ages. Pupae complete their development in from two to six days at {{convert|35|°C}}, but may take 20 days or more at {{convert|14|°C}}.<ref name=IFAS/>

When [[metamorphosis]] is complete, the adult fly emerges from the pupa. To do this, it uses the [[ptilinum]], an eversible pouch on its head, to tear open the end of the pupal case. The adult housefly lives from two weeks to a month in the wild, or longer in [[benign]] laboratory conditions. Having emerged from the pupa, it ceases to grow; a small fly is not necessarily a young fly, but is instead the result of getting insufficient food during the larval stage.<ref name=IFAS/>

Male houseflies are sexually mature after 16 hours and females after 24. Females produce a [[pheromone]], [[(Z)-9-Tricosene|(Z)-9-tricosene (muscalure)]]. This cuticular hydrocarbon is not released into the air and males sense it only on contact with females;<ref name=insencyc>{{Cite book|author=Dahlem, Gregory A.| pages=469–470|chapter=House Fly (Musca domestica) |title=Encyclopedia of Insects|edition=2|editor1=Resh, Vincent H.| editor2=Carde, Ring T.|year=2009| publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> it has found use as in pest control, for luring males to fly traps.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.0050228| pmid=17713987| year=2007| last1=Thom | first1=C.| last2=Gilley | first2=D.| last3=Hooper | first3=J.| last4=Esch | first4=H.| title=The scent of the waggle dance| volume=5| issue=9| pages=e228| pmc=1994260| journal=PLoS Biology }}</ref><ref name=epa>{{cite web | url=https://www3.epa.gov/pesticides/chem_search/reg_actions/reregistration/fs_PC-103201_1-Sep-94.pdf | title=(Z)-9-Tricosene (103201) Fact Sheet | publisher=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]|accessdate = 8 December 2017}}</ref> The male initiates the mating by bumping into the female, in the air or on the ground, known as a "strike". He climbs on to her thorax, and if she is receptive, a courtship period follows, in which the female vibrates her wings and the male strokes her head. The male then reverses onto her abdomen and the female pushes her [[ovipositor]] into his genital opening; copulation, with sperm transfer, lasts for several minutes. Females normally mate only once and then reject further advances from males,  while males mate multiple times.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Murvosh, C.M.|author2= Fye, R.L.|author3= LaBrecque, G.C. |year=1964 |title=Studies on the mating behavior of the house fly, ''Musca domestica'' L. |journal=Ohio Journal of Science |volume=64 |issue=4 |pages=264–271 |url=https://kb.osu.edu/dspace/handle/1811/5017}}</ref> A volatile semiochemical that is deposited by females on their eggs attracts other gravid females and leads to clustered egg deposition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jiang|first=Yong |last2=Lei|first2=Chao-liang |last3=Niu|first3=Chang-ying |last4=Fang|first4=Yu-ling |last5=Xiao|first5=Chun |last6=Zhang|first6=Zhong-ning |date=October 2002|title=Semiochemicals from ovaries of gravid females attract ovipositing female houseflies, Musca domestica|url=http://ir.ioz.ac.cn/bitstream/000000/6823/1/156-Semiochemicals%20from%20ovaries%20of%20gravid%20fema.pdf|journal=Journal of Insect Physiology|volume=48|issue=10|pages=945–950|issn=1879-1611|pmid=12770041|via= |doi=10.1016/s0022-1910(02)00162-2}}</ref>

The larvae depend on warmth and sufficient moisture to develop; generally, the warmer the temperature, the faster they grow. In general, fresh swine and chicken manures present the best conditions for the developing larvae, reducing the larval period and increasing the size of the pupae. Cattle, goat, and horse manures produce fewer, smaller pupae, while fully composted swine manure, with a water content under 40%, produces none at all.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Breitwart et al |title=Favorability of conditions in the reproduction and development of the common housefly: a controlled study |journal=International Journal of Entomology |date=2008 |volume=21 |issue=11 |pages=157-181}}</ref> Pupae can range from about {{convert|8.0|to|20|mg|oz|4|abbr=off}} under different conditions.<ref>{{cite journal | author1=Larraín, Patricia|author2= Salas, Claudio  | year=2008 | title=House fly (''Musca domestica'' L.) (Diptera: Muscidae) development in different types of manure [Desarrollo de la Mosca Doméstica (''Musca domestica'' L.) (Díptera: Muscidae) en Distintos Tipos de Estiércol] | journal=Chilean Journal of Agricultural Research | volume=68 | pages=192–197 | issn=0718-5839 | doi=10.4067/S0718-58392008000200009  | issue=2| last3=Salas F }}</ref>

The lifecycle can be completed in seven to 10 days under optimal conditions, but may take up to two months in adverse circumstances. In temperate regions, 12 generations may occur per year, and in the tropics and subtropics, more than 20.<ref name=IFAS/>

==Ecology==
[[File:Housefly pupae killed by wasp larvae.jpg|thumb|left|Housefly pupae killed by [[parasitoid wasp]] larvae: Each pupa has one hole through which a single adult wasp has emerged; the wasp larvae fed on the housefly larvae.]]

Houseflies play an important ecological role in breaking down and recycling organic matter. Adults are mainly [[Carnivore|carnivorous]]; their primary food is animal matter, [[carrion]], and [[faeces]], but they also consume milk, sugary substances, and rotting fruit and vegetables. Solid foods are softened with saliva before being sucked up.<ref name=Mehlhorn/> They can be opportunistic blood feeders.<ref>West (1951):189.</ref> Houseflies have a [[Mutualism (biology)|mutualistic]] relationship with the bacterium ''[[Klebsiella oxytoca]]'', which can live on the surface of housefly eggs and deter fungi which compete with the fly larvae for nutrients.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Lam, Kevin|author2= Thu,  Kelsie|author3= Tsang, Michelle|author4= Moore, Margo|author5= Gries, Gerhard |year=2009 |title=Bacteria on housefly eggs, ''Musca domestica'', suppress fungal growth in chicken manure through nutrient depletion or antifungal metabolites |journal=Naturwissenschaften |volume=96 |issue=9 |pages=1127–1132 |doi=10.1007/s00114-009-0574-1 |bibcode=2009NW.....96.1127L }}</ref>

Adult houseflies are diurnal and rest at night. If inside a building after dark, they tend to congregate on ceilings, beams, and overhead wires, while out of doors, they crawl into foliage or long grass, or rest in shrubs and trees or on wires.<ref name=IFAS/> In cooler climates, some houseflies [[Hibernation|hibernate]] in winter, choosing to do so in cracks and crevices, gaps in woodwork, and the folds of curtains. They arouse in the spring when the weather warms up, and search out a place to lay their eggs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Where do flies go in winter? |author= |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/earth/story/20150204-flies-can-be-active-all-year |newspaper=BBC Earth |date=10 February 2015 |accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>

Houseflies have many predators, including birds, reptiles, amphibians, various insects, and spiders. The eggs, larvae, and pupae have many species of stage-specific [[parasite]]s and [[parasitoid]]s. Some of the more important are the parasitic wasps ''[[Muscidifurax uniraptor]]'' and ''[[Spalangia cameroni]]''; these lay their eggs in the fly larvae tissue and their offspring complete their development before the adult flies can emerge from the pupae.<ref name=IFAS/> [[Histeridae|Hister beetles]] feed on housefly larvae in manure heaps and the predatory mite ''Macrocheles muscae domesticae'' consumes housefly eggs, each mite eating 20 eggs per day.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vet.entomology.cals.cornell.edu/arthropod-identification/chicken-recommendations/house-flies |title=House flies |year=2017 |publisher=Cornell University: Department of Entomology  |accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Musca domestica mit cf Entomophthora muscae 4418.jpg|thumb|Housefly killed by the pathogenic fungus ''[[Entomophthora muscae]]'']]

Houseflies sometimes carry [[phoresis (biology)|phoretic]] (nonparasitic) passengers including [[mite]]s such as ''[[Macrocheles muscaedomesticae]]'',<ref name="Ho1990">{{cite journal |last1=Ho |first1=T. M. |title=Phoretic association between Macrocheles muscaedomesticae (Acari: Macrochelidae) and flies inhabiting poultry manure in Peninsular Malaysia |journal=Experimental & Applied Acarology |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=1990 |pages=61–68 |doi=10.1007/BF01193974}}</ref> and the [[pseudoscorpion]] ''[[Lamprochernes chyzeri]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Christophoryova |first1=Jana |last2=Stloukal |first2=Eduard |last3=Stloukalova |first3=Viera |title=First record of phoresy of pseudoscorpion ''Lamprochernes chyszeri'' in Slovakia (Pseudoscorpiones: Chernetidae)|journal=Folia faunistica Slovaca |date=2011 |volume=16 |issue=3|pages=139–142 |url=http://www.ffs.sk/pdf/FFS-16-26-Christophoryova-et-al-2011.pdf}}</ref>

The pathogenic fungus ''[[Entomophthora muscae]]'' causes a fatal disease in houseflies. After infection, the [[hypha|fungal hyphae]] grow throughout the body, killing the fly in about 5 days. Infected flies have been known to seek high temperatures that could suppress the growth of the fungus. Affected females tend to be more attractive to males, but the fungus-host interactions have not been fully understood.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1146/annurev.ento.51.110104.150941 |pmid=16332215 |url=http://socialevolution.ku.dk/papers/2006/roy2006.pdf |title=Bizarre Interactions and Endgames: Entomopathogenic Fungi and Their Arthropod Hosts |journal=Annual Review of Entomology |volume=51 |pages=331–57 |year=2006 |last1=Roy |first1=H. E. |last2=Steinkraus |first2=D. C. |last3=Eilenberg |first3=J. |last4=Hajek|first4=A. E. |last5=Pell |first5=J. K.}}</ref> The housefly also acts as the alternative host to the parasitic nematode ''[[Habronema muscae]]'' that attacks horses.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hewitt, C. Gordon |title=The House-Fly: ''Musca Domestica'' Linn: Its Structure, Habits, Development, Relation to Disease and Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2FYiIGjMsuYC |year=2011 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-23299-9 |pages=181–184}}</ref>

==Relationship with humans==

Flies are a nuisance, disturbing people at leisure and at work, but they are disliked principally because of their habits of contaminating foodstuffs. They alternate between breeding and feeding in dirty places with feeding on human foods, during which process they soften the food with saliva and deposit their faeces, creating a health hazard.<ref name=WHO>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/water_sanitation_health/resources/vector302to323.pdf |title=Houseflies |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref> However, fly larvae are as nutritious as [[fish meal]], and could be used to convert waste to [[aquaculture|feed for fish]] and [[animal husbandry|livestock]].<ref name="QiuHussein2017">{{cite journal |last1=Qiu |first1=Xinghui |last2=Hussein |first2=Mahmoud |last3=Pillai |first3=Viju V. |last4=Goddard |first4=Joshua M. |last5=Park |first5=Hui G. |last6=Kothapalli |first6=Kumar S. |last7=Ross|first7=Deborah A.|last8=Ketterings|first8=Quirine M. |last9=Brenna |first9=J. Thomas |last10=Milstein |first10=Mark B. |last11=Marquis |first11=Helene |last12=Johnson |first12=Patricia A. |last13=Nyrop|first13=Jan P. |last14=Selvaraj |first14=Vimal |title=Sustainable production of housefly (Musca domestica) larvae as a protein-rich feed ingredient by utilizing cattle manure |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=12 |issue=2|year=2017 |pages=e0171708 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0171708|pmid=28170420 |bibcode=2017PLoSO..1271708H |pmc=5295707}}</ref>

Flies have been used in art and artefacts in many cultures. In 16th- and 17th-century European [[vanitas]] paintings, flies sometimes occur as ''[[memento mori]]''. They may also be used for other effects as in the Flemish painting, the ''[[Master of Frankfurt]]'' (1496). Fly amulets were popular in ancient Egypt.<ref>{{cite book|pages=20, 27|author=Connor, Steven| publisher=Reaktion Books|year=2006| title=Fly |isbn=978-1861892942}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/objects/3246|title=Fly Pendants and Cylindrical and Spherical Beads, ca. 1539–1292 B.C.E. Gold, lapis lazuli, Length: 9 11/16 in. (24.6 cm). Brooklyn Museum, Charles Edwin Wilbour Fund, 08.480.198.|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref>

===As a disease vector===
[[File:07682jfFood cuisine dishes Baliuag, Bulacanfvf 18 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Housefly lapping up food from a plate<!--Philippines-->]]

Houseflies can fly for several miles from their breeding places,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Nazni, W.A. |author2= Luke, H.|author3= Wan Rozita, W.M. |author4= Abdullah, A.G.|author5= Sadiyah, I. |author6= Azahari, A.H. |author7= Zamree, I. |author8= Tan, S.B. |author9= Lee H.L. |author10=Sofian A.M. |year=2005 |title=Determination of the flight range and dispersal of the house fly, ''Musca domestica'' (L.) using mark release recapture technique |journal=Tropical Biomedicine |volume=22 |issue=1 |pages=53–61 |pmid=16880754}}</ref> carrying a wide variety of organisms on their hairs, mouthparts, vomitus, and faeces. Parasites carried include cysts of [[protozoa]], e.g. ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]'' and ''[[Giardia lamblia]]'' and eggs of helminths, e.g., ''[[Ascaris lumbricoides]]'', ''[[Trichuris trichiura]]'', ''[[Hymenolepis nana]]'', and ''[[Enterobius vermicularis]]''.<ref name=Szalanski/> Houseflies do not serve as a [[secondary host]] or act as a [[Natural reservoir|reservoir]] of any bacteria of medical or veterinary importance, but they do serve as mechanical vectors to over 100 [[pathogen]]s, such as those causing [[typhoid]], [[cholera]], [[salmonellosis]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Ostrolenk, M.|author2=Welch H. |year=1942 |title=The house fly as a vector of food poisoning organisms in food producing establishments |journal=American Journal of Public Health |volume=32 |issue=5 |pages=487–494 |doi=10.2105/ajph.32.5.487|pmid= |pmc=1526899}}</ref> [[bacillary dysentery]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Levine, O.S. |author2= Levine M.M. |year=1991 |title=House flies (Muscadomestica) as mechanical vectors of shigellosis |journal=Reviews of Infectious Diseases |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=688–696 |pmid=1925289 |doi=10.1093/clinids/13.4.688}}</ref> [[tuberculosis]], [[anthrax]], [[ophthalmia]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Förster, M.|author2= Klimpel, S. |author3=Sievert, K. |year=2009 |title=The house fly (''Musca domestica'') as a potential vector of metazoan parazites caught in a pig-pen in Germany |journal=Veterinary Parasitology |volume=160 |issue=1–2 |pages=163–167 |doi=10.1016/j.vetpar.2008.10.087 |pmid=19081196}}</ref> and pyogenic cocci, making them especially problematic in hospitals and during outbreaks of certain diseases.<ref name=Szalanski>{{cite journal |author1=Szalanski, A.L. |author2=Owens, C.B. |author3= Mckay, T. |author4=Steelman, C.D. |year=2004 |title=Detection of ''Campylobacter'' and ''Escherichia coli'' O157:H7 from filth flies by polymerase chain reaction |journal=Medical and Entomology |pmid=15347391|volume=18 |issue=3 |pages=241–246 |doi=10.1111/j.0269-283X.2004.00502.x}}</ref> Disease-causing organisms on the outer surface of the fly may survive for a few hours, but those in the crop or gut can be viable for several days.<ref name=WHO/> Usually, too few bacteria are on the external surface of the flies (except perhaps for ''[[Shigella]]'') to cause infection, so the main routes to human infection are through the fly's regurgitation and defecation.<ref name=Service>{{cite book|author=Service, Mike|title=Medical Entomology for Students|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wRrof4RLDuwC&pg=PA140 |year=2008 |publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-70928-6|pages=140–141}}</ref>

In the early 20th century, Canadian public health workers believed that the control of flies was important in controlling the spread of tuberculosis. A "swat that fly" contest was held for children in Montreal in 1912.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.erudit.org/en/journals/uhr/2007-v36-n1-uhr0596/1015818ar.pdf|author1=Minnett, V. |author2= Poutanen, M. |year=2007| title= Swatting Flies for Health:Children and Tuberculosis in Early Twentieth-Century Montreal. |journal= Urban History Review| volume=36| issue=1| pages=32–44|doi=10.7202/1015818ar}}</ref>  Flies were targeted in 1916, when a [[polio]] epidemic broke out in the eastern United States. The belief that fly control was key to disease control continued, with extensive use of insecticidal spraying, well until the mid 1950s, declining only after the introduction of [[Salk vaccine|Salk's vaccine]].<ref>{{cite journal |title="I Am the Baby Killer!" House Flies and the Spread of Polio |journal=American Entomologist |volume=62 |issue=2 |page=83 |year=2016 |last1=Cirillo |first1=Vincent J. |doi=10.1093/ae/tmw039}}</ref> In China, [[Mao Zedong]]'s [[Four Pests Campaign]] between 1958 and 1962 exhorted the people to catch and kill flies, along with rats, mosquitoes, and sparrows.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chineseposters.net/themes/four-pests.php |title=Eliminate the Four Pests (1958) |website=chineseposters.net |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref>

===In warfare===
{{further|Entomological warfare}}
[[File:Fly_bomber_Philadelphia.png|thumb|upright|Philadelphia Department of Health poster warning the public of fly hazards (''c.'' 1942)]]
During the [[Second World War]], the Japanese worked on [[entomological warfare]] techniques under [[Shirō Ishii]]. Japanese Yagi bombs developed at Pingfan consisted of two compartments, one with houseflies and another with a bacterial slurry that coated the flies prior to release. ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'', which causes cholera, was the bacterium of choice, and was used in China in [[Baoshan, Yunnan|Baoshan]] in 1942, and in northern [[Shandong]] in 1943. Baoshan had been used by the Allies and bombing produced epidemics that killed 60,000 people in the initial stages reaching a radius of 200&nbsp;km, which finally took a toll of 200,000 victims. The Shandong attack killed 210,000; the occupying Japanese troops had been [[vaccination|vaccinated]] in advance.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lockwood |first1=Jeffrey A. |title=Insects as Weapons of War, Terror, and Torture|journal=Annual Review of Entomology |volume=57 |pages=205–227 |year=2012  |doi=10.1146/annurev-ento-120710-100618 |pmid=21910635 }}</ref>

===In waste management===

The ability of housefly larvae to feed and develop in a wide range of decaying organic matter is important for recycling of nutrients in nature. This could be exploited to combat ever-increasing amounts of waste.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Miller, B.F. |author2= Teotia, J.S. |author3=Thatcher, T.O. |year=1974 |title=Digestion of poultry manure by ''Musca domestica'' |journal=British Poultry Science |pmid=4447887|volume=15 |issue=2 |page=231 |doi=10.1080/00071667408416100}}</ref> Housefly larvae can be mass-reared in a controlled manner in animal manure, reducing the bulk of waste and minimizing environmental risks of its disposal.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Cickova, H.|author2= Pastor B.|author3= Kozanek, M. |author4= Martinez-Sanchez, A. |author5=Rojo S. |author6=Takac, P. |year=2012 |title=Biodegradation of pig manure by the housefly, ''Musca domestica'': A viable ecological strategy for pig manure management |journal=PLoS ONE |pmid=22431982 |volume=7 |issue=3 |pages=e32798 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0032798 |pmc=3303781 |bibcode=2012PLoSO...732798C }}</ref><ref name="Zhu 2012 485–491">{{cite journal |author1=Zhu, F.X. |author2= Wang, W.P. |author3= Hong, C.L. |author4= Feng, M.G. |author5= Xue, Z.Y. |author6=Chen, X.Y. |author7= Yao, Y.L. |author8=Yu, M. |year=2012 |title=Rapid production of maggots as feed supplement and organic fertilizer by the two-stage composting of pig manure |journal=Bioresource Technology |pmid=22541952 |volume=116 |pages=485–491 |doi=10.1016/j.biortech.2012.04.008}}</ref> Harvested maggots may be used as feed for animal nutrition.<ref name="Zhu 2012 485–491"/><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Hwangbo, J. |author2= Hong, E.C.|author3= Jang, A.|author4= Kang, H.K.|author5= Oh, J.S. |author6= Kim, B.W. |author7=Park, B.S. |year=2009 |title=Utilization of house fly-maggots, a feed supplement in the production of broiler chickens |journal=Journal of Environmental Biology |pmid=20120505|volume=30 |issue=4 |pages=609–614}}</ref>

===Control===
[[File:Detail with fly 1742.png|thumb|left|Detail of a 1742 painting by [[Frans van der Mijn]] that uses a fly in a [[Renaissance]] allegory of touch theme]]
Flies can be controlled, at least to some extent, by physical, chemical, or biological means. Physical controls include screening with small mesh or the use of vertical strips of plastic or strings of beads in doorways to prevent entry of flies into buildings. Fans to create air movement or air barriers in doorways can deter flies from entering, and food premises often use ultraviolet light traps that electrocute insects. Sticky fly papers hanging from the ceiling can  also be effective.<ref name=Service/> Another approach is the elimination as far as possible of potential breeding sites. Keeping garbage in lidded containers and collecting it regularly and frequently, prevents any eggs laid from developing into adults. Unhygienic rubbish tips are a prime fly-breeding site, but if garbage is covered by a layer of soil, preferably daily, this can be avoided.<ref name=Service/>

Insecticides can be used. Larvicides kill the developing larvae, but large quantities may need to be used to reach areas below the surface. Aerosols can be used in buildings to "zap" flies, but outside applications are only temporarily effective. Residual sprays on walls or resting sites have a longer-lasting effect.<ref name=Service/> Many strains of housefly have become immune to the most commonly used [[insecticide]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Georghiou, G.P.|author2= Hawley, M.K. |title=Insecticide resistance resulting from sequential selection of houseflies in the field by organophosphorus compounds |journal=Bulletin of the World Health Organization |volume=45 |issue=1 |pages=43–51 |year=1971 |pmid=5316852 |pmc=2427889}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Keiding, J. |year=1975 |title=Problems of housefly (''Musca domestica'') control due to multiresistance to insecticides |journal=Journal of Hygiene, Epidemiology, Microbiology, and Immunology |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=340–355 |pmid=52667}}</ref>

Several means of [[biological pest control]] have been investigated. These include the introduction of another species, the [[Hermetia illucens|black soldier fly]] (''Hermetia illucens''), whose larvae compete with those of the housefly for resources.<ref name=DeBach>{{cite book|author1=DeBach, Paul|author2=Rosen, David|title=Biological Control by Natural Enemies |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K6dOAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA348 |year=1991|publisher=CUP Archive |isbn=978-0-521-39191-7 |page=348}}</ref> The introduction of [[dung beetle]]s to churn up the surface of a manure heap and render it unsuitable for breeding is another approach.<ref name=DeBach/> Augmentative biological control by releasing parasitoids can be used, but flies breed so fast that the natural enemies are unable to keep up.<ref name=Capinera>{{cite book|author=Capinera, John L.|title=Encyclopedia of Entomology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i9ITMiiohVQC&pg=PA1880 |year=2008 |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4020-6242-1 |page=1880}}</ref>

===In science===

The ease of culturing houseflies, and the relative ease of handling them when compared to the fruit fly ''[[Drosophila]]'', have made them useful as model organism for use in laboratories. The American entomologist [[Vincent Dethier]], in his humorous ''To Know A Fly'' (1962), pointed out that as a laboratory animal, houseflies did not trouble anyone sensitive to animal cruelty. Houseflies have a small number of chromosomes, haploid six or diploid 12.<ref>West (1951):96.</ref> Because the somatic tissue of the housefly consists of long-lived postmitotic cells, it can be used as an informative model system for understanding [[DNA damage theory of aging|cumulative age-related cellular alterations]]. Oxidative DNA damage 8-hydroxydeoxyguanosine <!-- (8-OHdG) --> in houseflies was found in one study to increase with age and reduce life expectancy supporting the hypothesis that oxidative molecular damage is a causal factor in senescence (aging).<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Agarwal, S. |author2= Sohal, R. S. |title=DNA oxidative damage and life expectancy in houseflies |journal=PNAS |volume=91 |issue=25 |pages=12332–12335 |date=December 1994 |pmid=7991627 |pmc=45431 |doi=10.1073/pnas.91.25.12332 |bibcode=1994PNAS...9112332A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Holmes, G. E. |author2=Bernstein, C. |author3= Bernstein, H. |title=Oxidative and other DNA damages as the basis of aging: a review |journal=Mutation Research |volume=275 |issue=3–6 |pages=305–315 |date=September 1992 |pmid=1383772 |doi=10.1016/0921-8734(92)90034-M}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Harris |last1=Bernstein |first2=Claire M. |last2=Payne |first3=Carol |last3=Bernstein |first4=Harinder |last4=Garewal |first5=Katerina |last5=Dvorak |year=2008 |chapter=Cancer and Aging as Consequences of Unrepaired DNA Damage |title=New Research on DNA Damages |editor1-first=Honoka |editor1-last=Kimura |editor2-first=Aoi |editor2-last=Suzuki |publisher=Nova Science Publishers |location=New York |pages=1–47 |chapterurl=https://www.novapublishers.com/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=43247 |isbn=978-1-60456-581-2}}</ref>

[[File:Songs of Innocence and of Experience copy F object 48 THE FLY 1794.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William Blake]]'s illustration of "The Fly" in ''[[Songs of Innocence and of Experience]]'', 1794]]

The housefly is an object of biological research, partly for its variable [[Sex-determination system|sex-determination]] mechanism. Although a wide variety of sex-determination mechanisms exists in nature (e.g. male and female [[heterogamy]], [[haplodiploidy]], environmental factors), the way sex is determined is usually fixed within a [[species]]. The housefly is, however, thought to exhibit multiple mechanisms for sex determination, such as male heterogamy (like most [[insect]]s and [[mammal]]s), female heterogamy (like birds), and maternal control over offspring sex. The exact mechanism of sex determination involved is unresolved,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dübendorfer, A. |author2= Hediger, M|author3= Burghardt, G|author4= Bopp, D |title=''Musca domestica'', a window on the evolution of sex-determining mechanisms in insects |journal=International Journal of Developmental Biology|year=2002 |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=75–79 |pmid=11902690}}</ref> but sexual differentiation is controlled as in other insects by an ancient [[evolutionary developmental biology|developmental switch]], [[doublesex]], which is regulated by the [[transformer (gene)|transformer]] protein in many different insects.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Verhulst |first1=Eveline C. |last2=van de Zande |first2=Louis |last3=Beukeboom |first3=Leo W. |title=Insect sex determination: it all evolves around ''transformer'' |journal=Current Opinion in Genetics & Development |date=August 2010 |volume=20 |issue=4 |pages=376–383 |doi=10.1016/j.gde.2010.05.001 |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0959437X10000791}}</ref> The antimicrobial peptides produced by housefly maggots are of pharmacological interest.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1093/aesa/saw083|title=Flourishing in Filth: House Fly–Microbe Interactions Across Life History|journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America|volume=110|pages=6|year=2017|last1=Nayduch|first1=Dana|last2=Burrus|first2=Roxanne G}}</ref>

In the 1970s, the aircraft modeller Frank Ehling constructed miniature balsa-wood aircraft powered by live houseflies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/insect-power |publisher=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |title=Insect Power| author=Hanser, Kathleen |date=26 June 2009 |access-date=7 December 2017}}</ref> Studies of tethered flies have helped in the understanding of insect vision, sensory perception, and flight control.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.kyb.mpg.de/fileadmin/user_upload/files/publications/pdfs/pdf196.pdf |doi=10.1016/S0921-8890(99)00055-X |title=On robots and flies: Modeling the visual orientation behavior of flies |journal=Robotics and Autonomous Systems |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=227 |year=1999 |last1=Huber |first1=Susanne A. |last2=Franz |first2=Matthias O. |last3=Bülthoff |first3=Heinrich H.}}</ref>

===In literature===

''[[The Impertinent Insect]]'' is a group of five fables, sometimes ascribed to [[Aesop]], concerning an insect, in one version a fly, which puffs itself up to seem important. In the Biblical [[Plagues of Egypt|fourth plague of Egypt]], [[fly|flies]] represent death and decay, while the [[Philistine]] god [[Beelzebub]]'s name may mean "lord of the flies".<ref>"The etymology of Beelzebul has proceeded in several directions. The variant reading Beelzebub (Syriac translators and Jerome) reflects a long-standing tradition of equating Beelzebul with the Philistine deity of the city of Ekron mentioned in 2 Kgs 1:2, 3, 6, 16. Baalzebub (Heb ba˓al zĕbûb) seems to mean "lord of flies" (HALAT, 250, but cf. LXXB baal muian theon akkarōn, "Baal-Fly, god of Akkaron"; Ant 9:2, 1 theon muian).", Lewis, "Beelzebul", in Freedman, D.N. (1996). Vol. 1: The Anchor Yale Bible Dictionary (639). New York: Doubleday.</ref> In [[Greek mythology]], [[Myiagros]] was a god who chased away flies during the sacrifices to [[Zeus]] and [[Athena]]; Zeus sent a fly to bite [[Pegasus]], causing [[Bellerophon]] to fall back to Earth when he attempted to ride the winged steed to [[Mount Olympus (Mountain)|Mount Olympus]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Parker, Robert |title=On Greek Religion |publisher=Cornell University Press |year=2011 |pages=105–106 |isbn=978-0801477355}}</ref> In the traditional [[Navajo people|Navajo]] religion, Big Fly is an important spirit being.<ref>{{cite book |title=Handbook of North American Indians |website=Humboldt State University |url=http://www.users.humboldt.edu/jwpowell/LelandWymanHONAI-NavajoCeremonialSystem,reduced.pdf |page=539 |chapter=Navajo Ceremonial System |author=Leland Clifton Wyman |format=PDF |year=1983 |quote=Nearly every element in the universe may be thus personalized, and even the least of these such as tiny Chipmunk and those little insect helpers and mentors of deity and man in the myths, Big Fly (''Dǫ’&#8202;soh'') and Ripener (Corn Beetle) Girl (''’Anilt’&#8202;ánii ’At’&#8202;ééd'') (Wyman and Bailey 1964:29&ndash;30, 51, 137&ndash;144), are as necessary for the harmonious balance of the universe as is the great Sun.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Navaho Indian Ethnoentomology |author1=Leland Clifton Wyman & Flora L. Bailey |series=Anthropology Series |issue=12–13 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tHl1AAAAMAAJ&q=Big+Fly |date=1964 |publisher=University of New Mexico Press |lccn=64024356}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.native-languages.org/legends-fly.htm |title=Native American Fly Mythology |publisher=Native Languages of the Americas |accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>

[[William Blake]]'s 1794 poem [[The Fly (poem)|"The Fly"]], part of his collection ''[[Songs of Experience]]'', deals with the insect's mortality, subject to uncontrollable circumstances, just like humans.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Miner, Paul |title=Blake's Swedenborgian Fly |journal=Notes and Queries |year=2011 |volume=58 |issue=4 |page=530}}</ref> [[Emily Dickinson]]'s 1855 [[poem]] "I Heard a Fly Buzz When I Died" speaks of flies in the context of death.<ref>{{cite book|author=Priddy, Anna |title=Bloom's How to Write about Emily Dickinson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqbDI_fcFF4C&pg=PA169 |year=2009 |publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-1240-4 |page=169}}</ref> In [[William Golding]]'s 1954 novel ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'', the fly is however a symbol of the children involved.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Golding|title=Lord of the Flies : Text , Criticism , Giossary and Notes |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jGBkCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA8 |year=2013 |publisher=Al Manhal |isbn=9796500118451 |page=8}}</ref>

[[Ogden Nash]]'s humorous two-line 1942 poem "God in His wisdom made the fly/And then forgot to tell us why." indicates the debate about the value of biodiversity, given that even those considered by humans as pests have their place in the world's ecosystems.<ref>{{cite book |author=Henschel, Joh R. |title=Toktok Talkie: Ancient Mariner to Zophosis Moralesi |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3sFRCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA6 |year=2015 |publisher=Wordweaver Publishing House |isbn=978-99945-82-04-4 |page=6 |quote=Ogden Nash was neither the first nor the last person to puzzle about the value of the fly, not only because flies are frequently considered a nuisance, but also because biodiversity in general is a puzzle. Nash's question can also be interpreted as going to the heart of conservation}}</ref>

