'''Tourism in Lesotho''' is a growing industry in the country.

In 2013, travel and tourism contributed about 5.5% to the [[GDP]] of [[Lesotho]], with this proportion expected to increase to 6.1% of GDP by 2024.<ref name=lesothoreview>{{cite web |url=http://www.lesothoreview.com/tourism-2015.php |title=Tourism |publisher=The Lesotho Review |accessdate=2015-10-31}}</ref> The sector employed 25,000 people in 2013, 4.6% of total national employment.<ref name=lesothoreview/>

Residents of [[South Africa]], which completely surrounds Lesotho, make up over 90% of the visitors to the country. Many trips are to visit friends and family.<ref name=lesothoreview/>

Various outdoor pursuits form the most popular leisure activities for tourists in the country. The mountainous terrain draws tourists for hiking, pony trekking and skiing, as well as the use of [[four-wheel drive]] trails. The [[Afriski]] ski resort operates during the winter months.

The most used entry-points into Lesotho include [[Moshoeshoe I International Airport]] and the land border crossing points of [[Maseru]] and [[Maputsoe]].<ref name="A.2015">{{cite book|author=Camillo, Angelo A.|title=Handbook of Research on Global Hospitality and Tourism Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vQx4CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA330|date=17 August 2015|publisher=IGI Global|isbn=978-1-4666-8607-6|pages=314–|chapter=Points and Means of Tourist Entry into Lesotho}}</ref>

Tourism in the country is overseen by the Ministry of Tourism, Environment & Culture, based in the capital, Maseru.

